[98.536549, "o", "  \u001b[92m│\u001b[0m\u001b[15;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[92m└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\u001b[0m\u001b[16;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[17;1H\u001b[2K                                                                 \u001b[2m4 calls │ 129,129 tokens │ $0.4480\u001b[0m\u001b[18;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[19;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[1m\u001b[96m\u001b[100m❯ Read back the audit-bash hook you just created and confirm it is registered and active.\u001b[0m\u001b[20;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[2m[\u001b[0m\u001b[92m✓\u001b[0m\u001b[2m] \u001b[0m\u001b[1;97mIteration 1 / 100\u001b[0m  \u001b[2m(31514 tok)\u001b[0m  \u001b[2m(6.7s)\u001b[0m\u001b[21;1H\u001b[2K\u001b[2m  Think: \u001b[0m\u001b[2mThe user wants me to read back the audit-bash hook and confirm it's registered/active. \u001b[0m\u001b[22;1H\u001b[2K         \u001b[2mI'll call hooks$read to get its full record and hooks$list to confirm it's in the live \u001b[0m\u001b[23;1H\u001b[2K         \u001b[2mregistry. These are independent, so I'll run both in one it"]
